              {
                "tool_call_id": "callf855c485fdf44e28aac1fc48",
                "content": "# SIFT Homework Report\n\n## Written Assignment: Perspective Projection Theory\n\n### Problem 1: Perspective Projection Analysis\n\n#### (a) Circle Projection Proof\n\n**Problem Statement**: Prove that a circle parallel to the image plane still projects as a circle, and derive the standard equation $(x - x_c)^2 + (y - y_c)^2 = r^2$.\n\n**Proof**:\n\nConsider a perspective projection system with the camera center at the origin $O(0, 0, 0)$ and the image plane at $z = -f$ (where $f > 0$ is the focal length).\n\nLet a circle in 3D space be defined on a plane parallel to the image plane at $z = Z_0$ (where $Z_0 < 0$ for objects in front of the camera). The circle has center $(X_c, Y_c, Z_0)$ and radius $R$.\n\nThe parametric equation of the circle is:\n$$\n\\begin{cases}\nX = X_c + R\\cos\\theta \\\\\nY = Y_c + R\\sin\\theta \\\\\nZ = Z_0\n\\end{cases}\n\\quad \\text{for } \\theta \\in [0, 2\\pi)\n$$\n\n**Perspective Projection Model**:\n\nFor a 3D point $(X, Y, Z)$, the perspective projection onto the image plane $z = -f$ is given by similar triangles:\n$$\nx = -f \\cdot \\frac{X}{Z}, \\quad y = -f \\cdot \\frac{Y}{Z}\n$$\n\nSubstituting the circle parametric equations:\n$$\nx = -f \\cdot \\frac{X_c + R\\cos\\theta}{Z_0} = -\\frac{fX_c}{Z_0} - \\frac{fR}{Z_0}\\cos\\theta\n$$\n$$\ny = -f \\cdot \\frac{Y_c + R\\sin\\theta}{Z_0} = -\\frac{fY_c}{Z_0} - \\frac{fR}{Z_0}\\sin\\theta\n$$\n\nLet:\n$$\nx_c = -\\frac{fX_c}{Z_0}, \\quad y_c = -\\frac{fY_c}{Z_0}, \\quad r = -\\frac{fR}{Z_0}\n$$\n\nNote that since $Z_0 < 0$ and $f > 0$, we have $r > 0$.\n\nTherefore:\n$$\nx = x_c + r\\cos\\theta, \\quad y = y_c + r\\sin\\theta\n$$\n\nThis is the parametric equation of a circle in the image plane with center $(x_c, y_c)$ and radius $r$.\n\nEliminating $\\theta$:\n$$\n(x - x_c)^2 + (y - y_c)^2 = r^2\\cos^2\\theta + r^2\\sin^2\\theta = r^2\n$$\n\n**Conclusion**: A circle parallel to the image plane projects to a circle in the image plane. The center scales by the factor $-f/Z_0$ and the radius scales by the same factor.\n\n---\n\n#### (b) Vanishing Point Derivation\n\n**Problem Statement**: Derive the vanishing point $(x_v, y_v)$ of a set of parallel lines on the plane $Ax + By + Cz + D = 0$ in the image.\n\n**Derivation**:\n\nConsider a set of parallel lines in 3D space with direction vector $\\vec{d} = (d_x, d_y, d_z)$. A line can be parametrized as:\n$$\n\\vec{P}(t) = \\vec{P_0} + t\\vec{d} = (X_0 + td_x, Y_0 + td_y, Z_0 + td_z)\n$$\n\nwhere $\\vec{P_0} = (X_0, Y_0, Z_0)$ is a point on the line.\n\nThe perspective projection of this line is:\n$$\nx(t) = -f \\cdot \\frac{X_0 + td_x}{Z_0 + td_z}, \\quad y(t) = -f \\cdot \\frac{Y_0 + td_y}{Z_0 + td_z}\n$$\n\nThe **vanishing point** is the limit as $t \\to \\infty$:\n$$\nx_v = \\lim_{t \\to \\infty} x(t) = \\lim_{t \\to \\infty} -f \\cdot \\frac{X_0 + td_x}{Z_0 + td_z} = -f \\cdot \\frac{d_x}{d_z}\n$$\n$$\ny_v = \\lim_{t \\to \\infty} y(t) = \\lim_{t \\to \\infty} -f \\cdot \\frac{Y_0 + td_y}{Z_0 + td_z} = -f \\cdot \\frac{d_y}{d_z}\n$$\n\n**For lines on the plane $Ax + By + Cz + D = 0$**:\n\nThe direction vector $\\vec{d}$ must be parallel to the plane, meaning $\\vec{d} \\cdot \\vec{n} = 0$ where $\\vec{n} = (A, B, C)$ is the plane normal:\n$$\nAd_x + Bd_y + Cd_z = 0\n$$\n\nSolving for the relationship:\n$$\nCd_z = -(Ad_x + Bd_y)",
